Controlling for confounders in penalized regression

Mandy Mejia

2023-09-26

Controlling for confounders in OLS

When teaching introductory linear regression, one of my favorite topics is adjusted variable plots (also known as “added variable plots”). The basic idea is this: say you want to relate two sets of predictor variables, \(\bf X\) and \(\bf Z\), to a single response variable \(\bf y\). One standard way to do this is through a multiple linear regression model, given in matrix/vector form by:

\[ {\bf y} = {\bf X}\boldsymbol\beta + {\bf Z}\boldsymbol\gamma + \boldsymbol\epsilon \]

But let’s say that \(\bf Z\) represents some control variables we definitely need to account for (e.g. age, sex), and we want to explore the nature of the relationship between \(\bf X\) and \(\bf y\), accounting for \(\bf Z\). Or imagine we want to fit a model relating \(\bf y\) to just \(\bf X\), controlling for \(\bf Z\) by “regressing it out” beforehand. As it turns out, you can prove mathematically (see below) that if you regress out \(\bf Z\) from both \(\bf X\) and \(\bf y\) then relate the adjusted \(\bf y\) to the adjusted \(\bf X\), you get the exact same estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) as in the multiple linear regression model stated above.

For the purpose of exploratory analysis, this is great news! We can simply (1) regress \(\bf Z\) from \(\bf X\) to produce \(\bf X^*\), (2) regress \(\bf y\) from \(\bf X\) to produce \(\bf y^*\), then (3) plot \(\bf y^*\) versus \(\bf X\)* to get a visual impression of the relationship between the two, while controlling for \(\bf Z\). A few things could be revealed: if \(\bf X\) and \(\bf Z\) are highly correlated, then after controlling for \(\bf Z\) we may see that \(\bf X\) does not add much. (Conversely, if we plotted \(\bf X\) against \(\bf y\) without adjusting for \(\bf Z\), the “marginal” relationship may appear strong, but this could just be driven by \(\bf Z\).) We could also see non-linear relationships between \(\bf X\) and y, which we should account for in the model to avoid a misspecified model. Or we may see evidence of interactions between variables. In any case, the ability to perform exploratory analysis between \(\bf X\) and y, while accounting for \(\bf Z\), is pretty convenient.

Simulated Data Example

Here’s an example of this using simulated data. For simplicity, consider the case of a single variable \(X\) and single variable \(Z\). In this example, both \(X\) and \(Z\) are correlated with \(y\), but there is also strong correlation between \(X\) and \(Z\). So after controlling for \(Z\), there will be a weaker relationship between \(X\) and \(y\). Adjusted variable plots, such as those shown below, allow us to visually explore this relationship.

Generate simulated data:

#generate 3 independent variables X, Y, Z
set.seed(45873)
xyz0 <- matrix(rnorm(100*3), nrow=3, ncol=100)

#induce correlations between X, Y and Z
(cor_xyz <- matrix(c(1, 0.7, 0.85, 0.7, 1, 0.6, 0.85, 0.6, 1), nrow=3))
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,] 1.00  0.7 0.85
## [2,] 0.70  1.0 0.60
## [3,] 0.85  0.6 1.00
library(expm)
cor_xyz_sqrt <- sqrtm(cor_xyz)
xyz <- t(cor_xyz_sqrt %*% xyz0)
cor(xyz) #this should be close to cor_xyz
##           [,1]      [,2]      [,3]
## [1,] 1.0000000 0.6822354 0.8799130
## [2,] 0.6822354 1.0000000 0.6422735
## [3,] 0.8799130 0.6422735 1.0000000
#define X, Y, Z
X <- xyz[,1]
Y <- xyz[,2]
Z <- xyz[,3]

Plot the marginal relationships between all three variables:

#plot marginal relationships
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(X, Y)
plot(Z, Y)
plot(X, Z)

Plot the marginal vs. adjusted relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\):

#adjust both X and Y for Z, adding back in the mean
Y_adj <- residuals(lm(Y ~ Z)) + mean(Y)
X_adj <- residuals(lm(X ~ Z)) + mean(X)

library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)
library(gridExtra)
p1 <- qplot(X, Y) + geom_smooth(method='lm') + ggtitle('Marginal Relationship') + theme_few() + ylim(-2.5, 2.5)
p2 <- qplot(X_adj, Y_adj) + geom_smooth(method='lm') + ggtitle('Adjusted Relationship') + theme_few() + ylim(-2.5, 2.5)
grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow=1)

The marginal relationship plot paints an overly optimistic picture of the relationship between \(X\) and \(y\) if \(Z\) is going to be accounted for in the model. By contrast, the adjusted relationship plot adjusts for \(Z\) so we can get an accurate visual picture of the relationship between \(X\) and \(y\), accounting for \(Z\).

We might also see non-linear relationships between \(x\) and \(y\), which we should build into the model to avoid a misspecified model. Here’s a simple simulated example where \(y\) is related to \(x\) in a non-linear way

#use the correlated x and z from above
#simulate y = beta0 + beta1*x^2 + gamma*z
beta0 <- 2
beta1 <- -2
gamma <- 5
Y <- beta0 + beta1*X^2 + gamma*Z + rnorm(100, mean = 0, sd = 0.1)

The true relationship between \(x\) and \(y\), for a fixed value of \(z\), looks like this:

X_sort <- sort(X)
Y_fn_X <- beta1*X_sort^2 
plot(X_sort, Y_fn_X, type='l', main='Relationship between X and Y, Given Z')

If we just visualize the marginal relationship between X and Y, this is not at all clear. But if we first adjust for Z, we start to see clear non-linear patterns. With this knowledge, we can incorporate non-linear terms in the model to provide enough flexiblity to capture non-linear associations.

Plot the marginal relationships between all three variables:

#plot marginal relationships
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(X, Y)
plot(Z, Y)
plot(X, Z)

Plot the marginal vs. adjusted relationship between \(x\) and \(y\):

#adjust both X and Y for Z, adding back in the mean
Y_adj <- residuals(lm(Y ~ Z)) + mean(Y)
X_adj <- residuals(lm(X ~ Z)) + mean(X)

p1 <- qplot(X, Y) + geom_smooth() + ggtitle('Marginal Relationship') + theme_few() + ylim(-2.5, 2.5)
p2 <- qplot(X_adj, Y_adj) + geom_smooth() + ggtitle('Adjusted Relationship') + theme_few() + ylim(-2.5, 2.5)
grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow=1)

The true U-shaped relationship is much better revealed with the adjusted variable plot.

Proof of Adjusted Variables in OLS

To show this mathematically, first we must introduce some formalities. Let \(\bf H\) denote the “hat matrix” when the design matrix is \(\bf Z\), namely

\[ {\bf H} = {\bf Z}({\bf Z'Z})^{-1}{\bf Z'} \]

Recall that \(\bf H\) “puts the hat on” \(\bf y\) when predicting \(\bf y\) from \(\bf Z\), i.e. \(\hat{\bf y} = \bf Hy\). The residuals are given by \(\hat{\bf y} - {\bf y} = \bf (I-H)y\), which are what we mean when we say “\(\bf y\) adjusted for \(\bf Z\)”, which we are calling \(\bf y^*\). So \(\bf y^* = (I-H)y\), and \(\bf X^* = (I-H)X\), where in both cases \(\bf H\) is the hat matrix when the design matrix is \(\bf Z\).

Now that we have our adjusted variables \(\bf y^*\) and \(\bf X^*\), we can relate them through the model

\[ {\bf y}^* = {\bf X}^*\boldsymbol\beta + \boldsymbol\epsilon \] We can show mathematically that the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) in this model is exactly equal to the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol \beta\) in the earlier model with \(\bf X\) and \(\bf Z\). First, let’s work out the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol \beta\) in this model relating \(\bf y^*\) to \(\bf X^*\). We will use the fact that \(\bf I - H\) is symmetric and idempotent, meaning that \(\bf (I - H)(I - H) = (I - H)\).

\[ \hat{\boldsymbol\beta}^* = ({{\bf X}^*}'{\bf X}^*)^{-1}{{\bf X}^*}'{{\bf y}^*} = ({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf X})^{-1}{{\bf X}}'({\bf I - H}){{\bf y}} \]

That was the easy part. :) Now let’s work out the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol \beta\) in the earlier model relating \(\bf y\) to \(\bf X\) and \(\bf Z\).

\[ \begin{pmatrix} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta} \\ \hat{\boldsymbol\gamma} \end{pmatrix} = ([{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'[{\bf X}{\bf Z}])^{-1}[{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'{\bf y} = \begin{pmatrix} {\bf X}'{\bf X} & {\bf X}'{\bf Z} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf X} & {\bf Z}'{\bf Z} \end{pmatrix}^{-1} \begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix} =: {\bf A}\begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix} \] Since we are mainly interested in \(\boldsymbol\beta\), we need to work out the (1,1) and (1,2) blocks of \(\bf A\), the inverse of the block matrix that appears above. Using standard formulas for block matrix inverses, we can obtain

\[\begin{align*} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta} &= {\bf A}_{(1,1)}{\bf X}'{\bf y} + {\bf A}_{(1,2)}{\bf Z}'{\bf y} \\ &= ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf y} - ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf y} \\ &= ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf y} - ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y} \\ &= ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X})^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y})\\ &= ({\bf X}({\bf I - H}){\bf X})^{-1}({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf y})\\ &= ({\bf X}^*{\bf X}^*)^{-1}({\bf X^*}'{\bf y}^*)\\ \end{align*}\]

Voila, it works!

Proof of Adjusted Variables in Penalized Regression

In many applications including my personal research, \(\bf X\) is high-dimensional with the number of columns/variables p (much) greater than the number of rows/observations n. In this case, it’s common to use penalized regression techniques like ridge regression or LASSO. Does the result above hold in this context? That is, if we regress out confounders \(\bf Z\) from \(\bf X\) and from \(\bf y\) beforehand

If we fit a model relating a high-dimensional set of predictors \(\bf X\) to \(\bf y\) with either ridge or LASSO, the estimator for \(\beta\) is given by

\[ \hat{\boldsymbol\beta} = ({{\bf X}}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I})^{-1}{{\bf X}}'{{\bf y}} \] where \(\lambda\) is a penalty parameter that is typically determined via cross-validation. If we also include confounders \(\bf Z\) in the model, we can avoid including them in the penalization by setting \(\lambda = 0\) for those variables. So our penalty matrix, rather than \(\lambda \bf I\), becomes a block-diagonal matrix with \(\lambda \bf I\) defining the upper-left block and zeros everywhere else.

As before, we can work out the estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) in the case of a penalty on \(\bf X\):

\[\begin{align*} \begin{pmatrix} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta}^R \\ \hat{\boldsymbol\gamma}^R \end{pmatrix} &= \left\{[{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'[{\bf X}{\bf Z}] + \begin{pmatrix}\lambda{\bf I}_p^{-1} & {\bf 0} \\ {\bf 0} & {\bf 0} \end{pmatrix}\right\}^{-1} [{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'{\bf y} \\ &= \left\{\begin{pmatrix} {\bf X}'{\bf X} & {\bf X}'{\bf Z} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf X} & {\bf Z}'{\bf Z} \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix}\lambda{\bf I}_p^{-1} & {\bf 0} \\ {\bf 0} & {\bf 0} \end{pmatrix}\right\}^{-1} \begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix} \\ &= \begin{pmatrix} {\bf X}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p & {\bf X}'{\bf Z} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf X} & {\bf Z}'{\bf Z} \end{pmatrix} ^{-1} \begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}\]

Again we can use block matrix inverse formulas to obtain the estimator for \(\boldsymbol\beta\). Skipping some steps this time, we obtain

\[\begin{align*} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta}^R &= \left(({\bf X}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p) - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf X}\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf y}) \\ &= \left(({\bf X}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p) - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X}\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y}) \\ &= \left(({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y}) \\ &= \left(({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf y}) \\ &= \left(({\bf X^*}'{\bf X^*} + \lambda{\bf I}_p\right)^{-1}({\bf X^*}'{\bf y^*}) \end{align*}\]

Success! This estimator for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) is the same as what we would get if we related \(\bf y^*\) (\(\bf y\) adjusted for \(\bf Z\)) against \(\bf X^*\) (\(\bf X\) adjusted for \(\bf Z\)) with a ridge or LASSO penalty. So the theory of adjusted variable plots in OLS holds for penalized regression methods like LASSO and ridge.

Proof of adjusted variables in OLS

To introduce some formalities, let \(\bf H\) denote the “hat matrix” when the design matrix is \(\bf Z\), namely

\[ {\bf H} = {\bf Z}({\bf Z'Z})^{-1}{\bf Z'} \]

Recall that \(\bf H\) “puts the hat on” \(\bf y\) when predicting \(\bf y\) from \(\bf Z\), i.e. \(\hat{\bf y} = \bf Hy\). The residuals are given by \(\hat{\bf y} - {\bf y} = ({\bf I-H}){\bf y}\), which are what we mean when we say “\(\bf y\) adjusted for \(\bf Z\)”, which here we are calling \(\tilde{\bf y}\). So \(\tilde{\bf y}= ({\bf I-H}){\bf y}\), and \(\tilde{\bf X}= ({\bf I-H}){\bf X}\), where in both cases \(\bf H\) is the hat matrix when the design matrix is \(\bf Z\).

Now that we have our adjusted variables \(\tilde{\bf y}\) and \(\tilde{\bf X}\), we can relate them through the model

\[ \tilde{\bf y} = \tilde{\bf X}\boldsymbol\beta + \boldsymbol\epsilon \]

We can show mathematically that the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) in this model is exactly equal to the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) in the earlier model with \(\bf X\) and \(\bf Z\). First, let’s work out the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) in this model relating \(\tilde{\bf y}\) to \(\tilde{\bf X}\). We will use the fact that \(\bf I - H\) is symmetric and idempotent, meaning that \((\bf I - H)(\bf I - H) = (\bf I - H)\).

\[ \tilde{\boldsymbol\beta} = ({\tilde{\bf X}}'\tilde{\bf X})^{-1}{\tilde{\bf X}}'{\tilde{\bf y}} = ({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf X})^{-1}{{\bf X}}'({\bf I - H}){{\bf y}} \]

That was the easy part. :) Now let’s work out the OLS estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) in the earlier model relating \(\bf y\) to \(\bf X\) and \(\bf Z\). The full design matrix in this model is \([\bf X \bf Z]\), and the full coefficient vector is \((\boldsymbol\beta' \boldsymbol\gamma')'\), so we can write the standard OLS estimator as:

\[ \begin{pmatrix} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta} \\ \hat{\boldsymbol\gamma} \end{pmatrix} = ([{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'[{\bf X}{\bf Z}])^{-1}[{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'{\bf y} = \begin{pmatrix} {\bf X}'{\bf X} & {\bf X}'{\bf Z} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf X} & {\bf Z}'{\bf Z} \end{pmatrix}^{-1} \begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix} =: {\bf A}\begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix} \]

Since we are mainly interested in \(\boldsymbol\beta\), we need to work out the \((1,1)\) and \((1,2)\) blocks of the matrix \(\bf A\) defined above. Using standard formulas for block matrix inverses, we can obtain

\[ \begin{align*} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta} &= {\bf A}_{(1,1)}{\bf X}'{\bf y} + {\bf A}_{(1,2)}{\bf Z}'{\bf y} \\ &= ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf y} - ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf y} \\ &= ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf y} - ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X})^{-1}{\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y} \\ &= ({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X})^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y})\\ &= ({\bf X}({\bf I - H}){\bf X})^{-1}({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf y})\\ &= (\tilde{\bf X}'\tilde{\bf X})^{-1}(\tilde{\bf X}'\tilde{\bf y})\\ \end{align*}\]

Voila, it works!

Proof of adjusted variables in penalized regression

In many applications including my personal research, \(\bf X\) is high-dimensional with the number of columns/variables \(p\) (much) greater than the number of rows/observations \(n\). In this case, it’s common to use penalized regression techniques like ridge regression or LASSO. Does the result above hold in this context? That is, if we regress out confounders \(\bf Z\) from \(\bf X\) and from \(\bf y\) beforehand, do we obtain the same estimates for the beta coefficients on \(\bf X\), versus including \(\bf Z\) in the model?

If we fit a model relating a high-dimensional set of predictors \(\bf X\) to \(\bf y\) with either ridge or LASSO, the estimator for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) is given by

\[ \hat{\boldsymbol\beta} = ({{\bf X}}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I})^{-1}{{\bf X}}'{{\bf y}}, \]

where \(\boldsymbol\lambda\) is a penalty parameter that is typically determined via cross-validation. If we also include confounders \(\bf Z\) in the model, we can avoid including them in the penalization by setting \(\boldsymbol\lambda=0\) for those variables. So our penalty matrix, rather than \(\boldsymbol\lambda\)I, becomes a block-diagonal matrix with \(\boldsymbol\lambda{\bf I}\) defining the upper-left block and zeros everywhere else.

As before, we can work out the estimate for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) in the case of a penalty on \(\bf X\):

\[ \begin{align*} \begin{pmatrix} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta}^R \\ \hat{\boldsymbol\gamma}^R \end{pmatrix} &= \left\{[{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'[{\bf X}{\bf Z}] + \begin{pmatrix}\lambda{\bf I}_p^{-1} & {\bf 0} \\ {\bf 0} & {\bf 0} \end{pmatrix}\right\}^{-1} [{\bf X}{\bf Z}]'{\bf y} \\ &= \left\{\begin{pmatrix} {\bf X}'{\bf X} & {\bf X}'{\bf Z} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf X} & {\bf Z}'{\bf Z} \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix}\lambda{\bf I}_p^{-1} & {\bf 0} \\ {\bf 0} & {\bf 0} \end{pmatrix}\right\}^{-1} \begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix} \\ &= \begin{pmatrix} {\bf X}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p & {\bf X}'{\bf Z} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf X} & {\bf Z}'{\bf Z} \end{pmatrix} ^{-1} \begin{pmatrix}{\bf X}'{\bf y} \\ {\bf Z}'{\bf y} \end{pmatrix}. \end{align*}\]

Again we can use block matrix inverse formulas to obtain the estimator for \(\boldsymbol\beta\). Skipping some steps this time, we obtain

\[ \begin{align*} \hat{\boldsymbol\beta}^R &= \left(({\bf X}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p) - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf X}\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf Z}({\bf Z}'{\bf Z})^{-1}{\bf Z}'{\bf y}) \\ &= \left(({\bf X}'{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p) - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X}\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y}) \\ &= \left(({\bf X}'{\bf X} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'{\bf y} - {\bf X}'{\bf H}{\bf y}) \\ &= \left(({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p\right)^{-1}({\bf X}'({\bf I - H}){\bf y}) \\ &= \left((\tilde{\bf X}'\tilde{\bf X} + \lambda{\bf I}_p\right)^{-1}(\tilde{\bf X}'\tilde{\bf y}) \end{align*}\]

Success! This estimator for \(\boldsymbol\beta\) is the same as what we would get if we related \(\tilde{\bf y}\) (\(\bf y\) adjusted for \(\bf Z\)) against \(\tilde{\bf X}\) (\(\bf X\) adjusted for \(\bf Z\)) with a ridge or LASSO penalty. So the theory of adjusted variable plots in OLS holds for penalized regression methods like LASSO and ridge.

Take home message

When “adjusting for” confounding variables prior to fitting a model focusing only on the variables of interest, it is important to regress the confounders out from both \(\bf X\) and \(\bf y\)! It is somewhat common to see \(\bf Z\) only regressed from \(\bf y\), disregarding the potential influence of \(\bf Z\) on \(\bf X\). This is a process known as “sequential processing” that can have unintended consequences. In the case of prediction of \(\bf y\) based on \(\bf X\), failing to adjust \(\bf X\) for \(\bf Z\) as well can lead to attenuated prediction coefficients and worse prediction accuracy. Whether you are using standard OLS or penalized regression in a high-dimensional setting, if you adjust both \(\bf y\) and \(\bf X\) for \(\bf Z\), you can rest assured that it is fully equivalent to including \(\bf Z\) as a confounder in your model.
